{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9baeac02-4cbc-42aa-863c-26433f4f5d9f","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** The test compiled and ran without issues:\n\n```\nnint size:   8 bytes\nSpan<nint>:  [0, 10, 20, 30]\nSpan<nuint>: [0, 100, 200, 300]\n```\n\nThe only requirement is enabling `AllowUnsafeBlocks` (needed for `sizeof(nint)`). The `stackalloc` itself works in a safe context too — you can drop the `unsafe` block if you don't need `sizeof`. Native-sized integers (`nint`/`nuint`, introduced in C# 9) are valid `stackalloc` element types just like `int` or `byte`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8a851e67-4a6d-4f7f-b7c1-5d4a8134c207","outputTokens":191,"requestId":"6C50:8F118:D51265:108C398:6A0128E0"},"id":"d948f64d-1cb9-4bd8-ba52-b9d45df96f35","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:55:02.023Z","parentId":"1cadbf70-6900-4972-a666-234b3658e009"}
